🟡 1️⃣ Definition

Adapter Pattern allows two incompatible interfaces to work together by converting one interface into another.

🎯 Core Idea
Client expects → Interface A
But we have → Interface B

Adapter converts B → A
🧠 2️⃣ Real-Life Analogy
🔌 Phone Charger
Indian socket (round pins)
US charger (flat pins)

Adapter → makes them compatible

👉 You don’t change:

Socket ❌

Charger ❌

👉 You add an adapter ✅

🔥 3️⃣ Problem It Solves
❌ Without Adapter
class OldPaymentSystem {
    void makePayment() {
        System.out.println("Old payment");
    }
}

Client expects:

interface PaymentProcessor {
    void pay();
}
❌ Problem
OldPaymentSystem old = new OldPaymentSystem();
old.pay(); // ❌ method not available

👉 Interfaces don’t match

✅ 4️⃣ Adapter Solution

👉 Create a class that bridges the gap

🧱 5️⃣ Structure
1️⃣ Target Interface (what client expects)
interface PaymentProcessor {
    void pay();
}
2️⃣ Adaptee (existing incompatible class)
class OldPaymentSystem {
    void makePayment() {
        System.out.println("Old payment system");
    }
}
3️⃣ Adapter
class PaymentAdapter implements PaymentProcessor {

    private OldPaymentSystem oldPayment;

    public PaymentAdapter(OldPaymentSystem oldPayment) {
        this.oldPayment = oldPayment;
    }

    public void pay() {
        oldPayment.makePayment(); // adapting
    }
}
4️⃣ Client Code
OldPaymentSystem oldSystem = new OldPaymentSystem();

PaymentProcessor processor = new PaymentAdapter(oldSystem);
processor.pay();
🔥 What Happened?
Client → calls pay()
Adapter → converts call
Old system → executes makePayment()
🧠 6️⃣ Step-by-Step Flow
1. Client calls → pay()
2. Adapter receives call
3. Adapter translates → makePayment()
4. Old system executes
🎯 Key Insight

Adapter does NOT change existing code—it wraps it.

🧩 7️⃣ Types of Adapter
✅ 1. Object Adapter (most common)
Uses composition (has-a relationship)
private OldPaymentSystem oldPayment;
🟡 2. Class Adapter (rare in Java)
Uses inheritance (extends)
class Adapter extends OldPaymentSystem implements Target
⚡ 8️⃣ When to Use

✔ Integrating legacy systems
✔ Third-party libraries
✔ Incompatible interfaces
✔ Reusing existing code

🚫 9️⃣ When NOT to Use

When interfaces already match

When you can modify original code

🧠 🔟 Real-World Examples
1️⃣ Java Collections
Arrays.asList()

👉 Converts array → List

2️⃣ Spring Framework

Adapting different controllers

HandlerAdapters internally

3️⃣ Logging frameworks

Adapters for different logging APIs

🔥 1️⃣1️⃣ Advantages

✔ Reuse existing code
✔ No modification required
✔ Decouples client from implementation
✔ Clean integration

⚠️ 1️⃣2️⃣ Disadvantages

❌ Adds extra layer
❌ Too many adapters → complexity

🔄 1️⃣3️⃣ Adapter vs Decorator (Important)
Feature	Adapter	Decorator
Purpose	Convert interface	Add behavior
Focus	Compatibility	Enhancement
Changes interface?	✅ Yes	❌ No
🧠 1️⃣4️⃣ Adapter vs Strategy
Feature	Adapter	Strategy
Purpose	Interface conversion	Behavior selection
Use case	Integration	Algorithm switching
🧾 1️⃣5️⃣ Final Interview Summary

Adapter Pattern converts one interface into another expected by the client, enabling incompatible classes to work together without modifying their code.

🔑 1️⃣6️⃣ Memory Trick
Adapter → “Make incompatible things work together”
